2. Objective

During this class we will apply in practice conditional entropy to the analysis of natural languages.

3. How do we know that hieroglyphs are a meaningful text?

Finding the Rosetta stone was crucial for deciphering Egyptian hieroglyphs. It was found in 1799 during Napoleon’s expedition to Egypt, and later in 1801 taken by Great Britain as a result of peace negotiations.

The stone tablet contains the same text written in three ways: hieroglyphs, demotic (“everyday-use hieroglyphs”), and Greek. Based on these findings, the bigger part of the hieroglyphic writing system was deciphered by 1822.

Finding similar translations allowed to decipher some other ancient languages. The Mesopotamian language was deciphered in 1857, and the Mayan language in 1952. However, there are still other ancient languages that remain incomprehensible to us.

The main question for those incomprehensible texts is: are those pictograms a system of writing at all? For example, the Indus Valley Civilization, which existed between 3300 and 1300 BC, left behind clay tablets containing several symbols each. Archeologists long disputed, whether it is writing system at all. The conditional entropy analysis gave the positive answer to this question.

4. Conditional entropy (recap)

Conditional entropy H(Y |X) measures the amount of uncertainty (entropy) of a random variable Y that remains, if we know the value of a random variable X. We can compute it using the formula:

$$ H(Y|X) =-\sum_{x \in X, y \in Y}p(x,y) · \log p(y|x) $$

where p(x, y) is the joint probability of events x and y, and p(y|x) is the probability of an event y dependent on x. The above formula can be derived from:

$$ H(Y|X) = \sum_{x \in X}p(x) · H(Y|X=x) = \sum_{x \in X}p(x) · [ -\sum_{y \in Y}p(y|x · \log p(y|x))] $$

Conditional entropy is used, for example, in the decision tree learning algorithms to (sort of greedily) select at each step an attribute which will minimize the conditional entropy of a decision attribute. When applying the above definition to the analysis of language, p(x, y) is the joint probability of an n-gram x and a following character/word y against all other possible (n+1)-grams in the corpus, and p(y|x) is the probability of y occurring after x. In the homework, we will consider the conditional entropy of rank n, where n denotes the length of an n-gram x. Conditional entropy H(Y |X) can be also computed as a difference between joint entropy H(Y, X) and (marginal) entropy H(X):

$$ H(Y|X) = H(Y, X) - H(X) = -\sum_{x \in X , y \in Y}p(x, y) · \log p(y,x) + \sum_{x \in X} p(x)·\log p(x)$$

5. The language of dolphins and the search for extraterrestrial civilizations

When researching the language of the civilization of ancient Indus, as well as all modern languages, we will notice that conditional entropy of different languages is similar and decreases as the rank becomes bigger. This is true for both the conditional entropy of characters and words. This is an expected result. Imagine that our task is to guess a word selected from a book. Our options are limited and we can only guess randomly, alternatively choose the most frequent word. If instead we were supposed to do the same but given the word that was before, our probability of success would be much higher. The task will be even simpler when we are provided with two previous words. The set of possible words decreases (for example, because of different parts of speech), certain words become much more probable (for example, “wise man” vs “wise politician”), or both of those effects at the same time. Since our uncertainty decreases, we can infer that the entropy also does so. A similar analysis was conducted on the noises generated by different species of animals in order to compare the complexity of their communication. The animals with high intelligence (or rather: the intelligence we as humans would be more apt to call as such), like for example dolphins, have the similar entropy characteristic of their communication system as human languages. This line of research interested the astronomer and astrophysicist Frank Drake. In 1959 he initiated the SETI (Search for Extraterrestrial Intelligence) project, which is continued to this day. The goal of this project is to find extraterrestrial civilizations by capturing and analyzing the radio and light signals coming to us from space. This search is conducted using, among others, the conditional entropy of signals.

from collections import Counter

def count_ngrams_prob(text, rank):
    n=rank+1
    # Counting n-grams
    n_grams = [text[i:i+n] for i in range(len(text)-n+1)]
    n_grams_counter = Counter(n_grams)
    # Counting probabilities
    n_grams_prob = {}
    for n_gram in n_grams_counter:
        n_grams_prob[n_gram] = n_grams_counter[n_gram] / len(n_grams)
    # sort n_grams_prob by values
    n_grams_prob = dict(sorted(n_grams_prob.items(), key=lambda item: item[1], reverse=True))
    return n_grams_prob

def count_words_prob(text, rank):
    #split text into pair of words
    input_words=text.split()
    group_of_words=[]
    for i in range(len(input_words)-rank):
        group_of_words.append(' '.join(input_words[i:i+rank+1]))
    words_counter = Counter(group_of_words)
    # Counting probabilities
    words_prob = {}
    for word in words_counter:
        words_prob[word] = words_counter[word] / len(group_of_words)
    # sort words_prob by values
    words_prob = dict(sorted(words_prob.items(), key=lambda item: item[1], reverse=True))
    return words_prob

import math

def entropy(text):
    n_grams_prob = count_ngrams_prob(text, 0)
    entropy = 0
    for n_gram in n_grams_prob:
        entropy -= n_grams_prob[n_gram] * math.log2(n_grams_prob[n_gram]) 
    return entropy

def words_entropy(text):
    words_prob = count_words_prob(text, 0)
    entropy = 0
    for word in words_prob:
        entropy -= words_prob[word] * math.log2(words_prob[word]) 
    return entropy

def conditional_entropy(text, rank):
    ngrams_prob = count_ngrams_prob(text, rank)
    n_one_grams_prob = count_ngrams_prob(text, rank-1)
    cond_entropy = 0
    for n_gram in ngrams_prob:
        cond_entropy -= ngrams_prob[n_gram] * math.log2(ngrams_prob[n_gram]/n_one_grams_prob[n_gram[:rank]])
    return cond_entropy

def words_conditional_entropy(text, rank):
    words_prob = count_words_prob(text, rank)
    words_one_prob = count_words_prob(text, rank-1)
    cond_entropy = 0
    for word in words_prob:
        cond_entropy -= words_prob[word] * math.log2(words_prob[word]/words_one_prob[' '.join(word.split()[:-1])])
    return cond_entropy

def compute_data(text, rank):
    y_letters = []
    y_words = []
    for r in range(rank):
        ent_l = conditional_entropy(text, r)
        ent_w = words_conditional_entropy(text, r)
        print('Rank: ', r, '| letterEntropy: ', ent_l, '| wordEntropy: ', ent_w)
        y_letters.append(ent_l)
        y_words.append(ent_w)
    return y_letters, y_words

def collect_data(rank, dataset = ['norm_wiki_en.txt', 'norm_wiki_eo.txt', 'norm_wiki_et.txt', 'norm_wiki_ht.txt', 'norm_wiki_la.txt', 'norm_wiki_nv.txt', 'norm_wiki_so.txt']):
    rank = rank + 1
    y_l=[]
    y_w=[]
    for data in dataset:
        print( 'Processing file: ', data )
        text = loading_file('samples/'+data)
        y_letters, y_words = compute_data(text, rank)
        y_l.append(y_letters)
        y_w.append(y_words)
    return y_l, y_w

import numpy as np

def compute_stats(y_l, y_w):
    y_l = np.array(y_l)
    y_w = np.array(y_w)
    y_l_mean = np.mean(y_l, axis=0)
    y_w_mean = np.mean(y_w, axis=0)
    y_l_std = np.std(y_l, axis=0)
    y_w_std = np.std(y_w, axis=0)
    y_l_max = np.max(y_l, axis=0)
    y_w_max = np.max(y_w, axis=0)
    y_l_min = np.min(y_l, axis=0)
    y_w_min = np.min(y_w, axis=0)
    return y_l_mean, y_w_mean, y_l_std, y_w_std, y_l_max, y_w_max, y_l_min, y_w_min

def print_stats(stats):
    print('N-GRAMS ENTROPY')
    y_l_mean, y_w_mean, y_l_std, y_w_std, y_l_max, y_w_max, y_l_min, y_w_min = stats
    print('Rank |   Mean   |   Std    |   Max    |    Min')
    for i in range(len(y_l_mean)):
        print(i, '   | ', round(y_l_mean[i], 4), ' | ', round(y_l_std[i], 4), ' | ', round(y_l_max[i], 4), ' | ', round(y_l_min[i], 4))
    print('\nWORDS ENTROPY')
    print('Rank |   Mean   |   Std    |   Max    |    Min')
    for i in range(len(y_w_mean)):
        print(i, '   | ', round(y_w_mean[i], 4), ' | ', round(y_w_std[i], 4), ' | ', round(y_w_max[i], 4), ' | ', round(y_w_min[i], 4))

import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot_stats(stats):
    y_l_mean, y_w_mean, y_l_std, y_w_std, y_l_max, y_w_max, y_l_min, y_w_min = stats
    x = [i for i in range(len(y_l_mean))]
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    plt.plot(x, y_l_mean, label='Mean')
    plt.fill_between(x, np.array(y_l_max), np.array(y_l_min), alpha=0.2)
    plt.fill_between(x, np.array(y_l_mean)-np.array(y_l_std), np.array(y_l_mean)+np.array(y_l_std), alpha=0.2)
    plt.legend()
    plt.title('Letter entropy')
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    plt.plot(x, y_w_mean, label='Mean')
    plt.fill_between(x, np.array(y_w_max), np.array(y_w_min), alpha=0.2)
    plt.fill_between(x, np.array(y_w_mean)-np.array(y_w_std), np.array(y_w_mean)+np.array(y_w_std), alpha=0.2)
    plt.legend()
    plt.title('Word entropy')
    plt.show()

def plot_analysis(stats, y_letters, y_words, dataset = ['sample0.txt', 'sample1.txt', 'sample2.txt', 'sample3.txt', 'sample4.txt', 'sample5.txt']):
    for data in dataset:
        print( 'Processing file: ', data )
        y_l_mean, y_w_mean, y_l_std, y_w_std, y_l_max, y_w_max, y_l_min, y_w_min = stats
        x = [i for i in range(len(y_l_mean))]
        plt.title('Entropy for ' + data)
        plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
        plt.plot(x, y_l_mean, label='Mean')
        plt.fill_between(x, np.array(y_l_max), np.array(y_l_min), alpha=0.2)
        plt.fill_between(x, np.array(y_l_mean)-np.array(y_l_std), np.array(y_l_mean)+np.array(y_l_std), alpha=0.2)
        plt.legend()
        plt.title('Letter entropy')
        plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
        plt.plot(x, y_w_mean, label='Mean')
        plt.fill_between(x, np.array(y_w_max), np.array(y_w_min), alpha=0.2)
        plt.fill_between(x, np.array(y_w_mean)-np.array(y_w_std), np.array(y_w_mean)+np.array(y_w_std), alpha=0.2)
        plt.legend()
        plt.title('Word entropy')

        y_l = y_letters[dataset.index(data)]
        y_w = y_words[dataset.index(data)]
        x = [i for i in range(len(y_l))]
        plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
        plt.plot(x, y_l, label=data)
        plt.legend()
        plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
        plt.plot(x, y_w, label=data)
        plt.legend()
        plt.show()
